\contentsline {figure}{\numberline {1}{\ignorespaces Schematic overview of CAPO. (a) Within-trajectory token dependence induces nontrivial covariance structure in trajectory gradients, which can amplify gradient variance as a function of response length. (b) CAPO reweights trajectories by learned posterior precisions (length and covariance-aware) to obtain an unbiased, lower-variance aggregate update.\relax }}{3}{figure.caption.1}%
\contentsline {figure}{\numberline {2}{\ignorespaces CAPO Model: Horizontal layout with enlarged plates and unified \scriptsize labeling.\relax }}{5}{figure.caption.2}%
\contentsline {figure}{\numberline {3}{\ignorespaces Training dynamics (validation Avg@8 vs. global step) for a representative subset of methods.\relax }}{52}{figure.caption.18}%
\contentsline {figure}{\numberline {4}{\ignorespaces Stability summary. Each point corresponds to a method, plotted by monotonicity (higher is better) and negative drift rate (lower is better).\relax }}{53}{figure.caption.20}%
\contentsline {figure}{\numberline {5}{\ignorespaces Verifier success by response-length decile. This analysis highlights whether a method disproportionately favors short (or long) trajectories even when end-to-end accuracy is similar.\relax }}{54}{figure.caption.21}%
\contentsline {figure}{\numberline {6}{\ignorespaces Synthetic benchmark: normalised mean-squared advantage $\mathbb {E}[A^2 \mid L] / \mathbb {E}[A^2 \mid L_{\min }]$ versus trajectory length under six covariance regimes. Curves above~$1$ indicate length amplification (long trajectories dominate the gradient); curves below~$1$ indicate precision-optimal suppression of noisy trajectories. GRPO amplifies long trajectories by $3$--$7\times $; LV-CAPO suppresses them by concentrating weight on high-precision (short) trajectories.\relax }}{56}{figure.caption.22}%
\contentsline {figure}{\numberline {7}{\ignorespaces Signal allocation across length bins. Each bar shows the fraction of total $\DOTSB \sum@ \slimits@ _i A_i^2$ contributed by a given length bin. GRPO over-allocates to the longest bin; CAPO shifts signal towards shorter trajectories where the signal-to-noise ratio is highest.\relax }}{57}{figure.caption.23}%
\contentsline {figure}{\numberline {8}{\ignorespaces Baseline-MSE relative efficiency $\mathrm {Var}(\hat m_{\text {unif}}) / \mathrm {Var}(\hat m_M)$ across methods and covariance regimes. Values above $1.0$ indicate strictly lower-variance baseline estimation than uniform averaging. LV-CAPO achieves $2$--$6\times $ relative efficiency under dependence, the theoretical optimum for inverse-variance weighting.\relax }}{58}{figure.caption.24}%
